The catch-curve plot \figrefp{fig:CatchCurveBrkTrt1} was produced with \R{plot()} as follows\footnote{Note that \R{pch=19} simply forces \R{plot()} to use filled circles as points.}  
<<CatchCurveBrkTrt1, fig.cap="Catch curve for the Tobin Harbor Brook Trout data.">>=
plot(logct~age,data=bkt,ylab="log(Catch)",pch=19)
@

From the initial catch curve plot it was determined that the descending limb consisted of ages 2 through 6.  Thus, a new data frame which contains only the information for these ages on the descending limb should be extracted with \R{Subset()}, which requires the original data frame as the first argument and a conditioning statement as the second argument.  Thus, the data for ages 2 to 6 were isolated with
<<>>=
( bkt.d <- Subset(bkt,age >= 2) )
@

A linear regression model is fit with \R{lm()} using a formula of the form \R{y}\verb+~+\R{x} as the first argument and the appropriate data frame in \R{data=}.  The result should be saved to an object so that other information can be extracted from the results.  For example, the fitted coefficients are extracted with \R{coef()} and corresponding confidence intervals with \R{confint()}.  Thus, the linear regression of log catch-at-age on age for only the descending limb is fit and then seen with
<<>>=
cc <- lm(logct~age,data=bkt.d)
coef(cc)
confint(cc)
@

The negative of the slope from fitting this model is the estimate of $Z$, or $\hat{Z}$.  Because $\hat{Z}$ is essentially the slope of this model, the confidence interval for the slope is also the confidence interval for $Z$.    Thus, from these results it is seen that $\hat{Z}$ is \Sexpr{formatC(-coef(cc)[2],format="f",digits=2)} with a 95\% confidence interval between \Sexpr{formatC(-confint(cc)[2,2],format="f",digits=2)} and \Sexpr{formatC(-confint(cc)[2,1],format="f",digits=2)}.

The estimated annual mortality rate ($\hat{A}$), with confidence interval, can be computed by extracting the slope information from the previous results and using $A=1-e^{-Z}$.  For example,

<<>>=
( A <- 1-exp(coef(cc)[2]) )
( A.ci <- 1-exp(confint(cc)[2,]) )
@

Thus, the estimated annual mortality rate is \Sexpr{formatC(100*(1-exp(coef(cc)[2])),format="f",digits=1)}\% with an approximate 95\% confidence interval between \Sexpr{formatC(100*A.ci[2],format="f",digits=1)}\% and \Sexpr{formatC(100*A.ci[1],format="f",digits=1)}\%.


\subsection{\R{catchCurve()} Convenience Function}
The catch curve analysis depicted in the previous section can be more efficiently obtained with \R{catchCurve()}, which requires three arguments.  The first argument is a formula of the form \R{catch}\verb"~"\R{age} where \R{catch} and \R{age} generically represent the variables containing the catches and ages for the catch curve.  A \R{data=} argument set to the data frame containing the catch and age variables is also required.  This data frame does NOT have to consist of only the descending limb of the catch curve.  The required \R{ages2use=} argument is a vector identifying the ages corresponding to the descending limb of the catch curve.  The results of \R{catchCurve()} should be saved to an object which is then submitted to \R{summary()} to obtain the estimated $Z$ and $A$ values\footnote{The \R{summary()} and \R{confint()} functions can also take an optional \R{type="lm"} argument to return the summary and confidence intervals for the slope and intercept of the linear model.}, to \R{confint()} to obtain the confidence intervals for $Z$ and $A$, and to \R{plot()} to return the catch-curve with the descending limb highlighted, the regression model superimposed, and the mortality rate estimates printed.

The catch curve analysis for the Tobin Harbor Brook Trout using ages two through six, with illustrative plot \figrefp{fig:CatchCurveBrkTrt2}, is obtained with
<<CatchCurveBrkTrt2, fig.cap="Catch curve for the Tobin Harbor Brook Trout data.">>=
thcc <- catchCurve(ct~age,data=bkt,ages2use=2:6)
summary(thcc)
confint(thcc)
plot(thcc)
@

\subsection{Weighted Catch-Curve Regression}
\cite{MaceinaBettoli1998} suggested that a weighted regression should be used with the catch-curve method in order to reduce the relative impact of older ages with fewer fish.  They suggested that an unweighted regression should be fit to the descending limb of the catch curve and that the resultant model should be used to predict the natural log number of fish in each age class.  These predictions can then serve as the weights to a second regression of the natural log of catches on age.  The methodology of \cite{MaceinaBettoli1998} is implemented with \R{catchCurve()} by including the \R{use.weights=TRUE} argument.  This is illustrated below for the Tobin Harbor Brook Trout data,
<<>>=
thcc2 <- catchCurve(ct~age,data=bkt,ages2use=2:6,use.weights=TRUE)
summary(thcc2)
confint(thcc2)
@

\subsection{Which Ages?}
\cite{Smithetal2012}, in a simulation study, suggested that the first age to be included on the descending limb is the age where the peak catch occurred (in contrast to one year after the peak catch).  \cite{ChapmanRobson1960} proposed that the regression methods should exclude all age-classes above the age where the catches fall below five individuals.  \cite{Dunnetal2002} considered a modification of this suggestion where the cutoff catch value is one individual.  In their analyses, \cite{Dunnetal2002} found that their modified suggestion generally performed better than the regression using all available age-classes, but that the suggestion of \cite{ChapmanRobson1960} actually performed worse.  \cite{Smithetal2012}, however, showed that the weighted regression method was less biased than the unweighted regression method no matter what decision rule was used for the oldest age in the analysis.  Thus, if the regression method is used (see \sectref{sect:CompareMethods}) it is suggested that a weighted regression that uses all age-classes older than and including the age with the maximum catch should be used.


\section{Chapman-Robson Method} \label{sect:ChapmanRobson}
\subsection{Background}
\cite{ChapmanRobson1960} (and \cite{RobsonChapman1961}) provided an alternative method for estimating the total annual survival rate ($S$), and thus the annual ($A$) and instantaneous ($Z$) total mortality rates, from catch curve data.  Their method was based on understanding that the catches at each age on the descending limb of the catch curve followed a geometric probability distribution and using this to derive a maximum likelihood estimator for the survival parameter of the distribution.  Their method, called the Chapman-Robson method, is outlined below and the derivation of their method is shown in \appref{appsect:ChapmanRobson}.

The Chapman-Robson estimate of the annual survival rate is

\begin{equation}  \label{eqn:ChapmanRobsonS}
  \hat{S} = \frac{T}{n+T-1} = \frac{\bar{T}}{1+\bar{T}-\frac{1}{n}}
\end{equation}

where $n$ is the total number of fish observed on the descending limb of the catch curve, $T$ is the total recoded age of fish on the descending limb of the catch curve, and $\bar{T}$ is the mean recoded age of fish on the descending limb of the catch curve (i.e., $\bar{T}=\frac{T}{n}$).  It should be noted that the ages are ``recoded'' such that the first fully-recruited age on the descending limb of the catch-curve is set to 0.  The total recoded age is calculated as a weighted sum of the recoded ages where the weights are the catches at each age.  The standard error of this estimate is

\begin{equation}  \label{eqn:ChapmanRobsonSSE1}
  SE_{\hat{S}} = \sqrt{\frac{T}{n+T-1}\left(\frac{T}{n+T-1}-\frac{T-1}{n+T-2}\right)} = \sqrt{\hat{S}\left(\hat{S}-\frac{T-1}{n+T-2}\right)}
\end{equation}

If $n$ is large, as it often is in fisheries catch data, then $SE_{\hat{S}}$ can be estimated by

\begin{equation}  \label{eqn:ChapmanRobsonSSE2}
  SE_{\hat{S}} = \sqrt{\frac{\hat{S}(1-\hat{S})^{2}}{n}}
\end{equation}

The Chapman-Robson estimate of $S$ can be transformed into an estimate of $Z$ through the relationship $S=e^{-Z}$, i.e., $\hat{Z} = -log(\hat{S})$ with a large sample approximation of $SE_{\hat{Z}}$ \citep{Jensen1985} as

\begin{equation}  \label{eqn:ChapmanRobsonZSE}
  SE_{\hat{Z}} = \frac{SE_{\hat{S}}}{\hat{S}}
\end{equation}

\cite{Hoenigetal1983}, however, have shown that these estimates are slightly biased and that an unbiased estimate of $Z$ is obtained with

\begin{equation}  \label{eqn:ChapmanRobsonZ2}
  \hat{Z} = -log(\hat{S}) - \frac{(n-1)(n-2)}{n(T+1)(N+T-1)}
\end{equation}

with the large sample approximation of $SE_{\hat{Z}}$ as

\begin{equation}  \label{eqn:ChapmanRobsonZSE2}
  SE_{\hat{Z}} = \frac{1-e^{-\hat{Z}}}{\sqrt{ne^{-\hat{Z}}}}
\end{equation}

These calculations are illustrated below with the Tobin Harbor Brook Trout (assuming that the fish were fully recruited to the fyke nets at age-2).  The original data \tabrefp{tab:BrkTrtData} were modified for calculation of the Chapman-Robson estimator of $S$ as shown in \tabrefp{tab:BrkTrtDataCR}.  From that, it is seen that $n=235$ and $T=229$.  Thus, 
\begin{align}
\hat{S} &= \frac{229}{235+229-1} = 0.4946004 \\
SE_{\hat{S}} &= \sqrt{0.4946004\left(0.4946004-\frac{229-1}{235+229-2}\right)} = 0.02326041
\end{align}

An approximate 95\% confidence interval for $S$ is $0.4946\pm1.96(0.0233)$ or (0.4490,0.5402).  Furthermore,

\begin{align}
\hat{Z} &= -log(0.4946004) - \frac{(235-1)(235-2)}{235(229+1)(235+229-1)} = 0.7018264 \\
SE_{\hat{Z}} &= \frac{1-e^{-0.7018264}}{\sqrt{235*e^{-0.7018264}}} = 0.04672751
\end{align}

An approximate 95\% confidence interval for $Z$ is $0.7018\pm1.96(0.0467)$ or (0.6102,0.7934).

